      <hedline>
        <hl1>Henrys All Around</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Daniel Pollack-Pelzner letter comments on August 10 article on production of Shakespeare's plays abroad</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Marathon of Richards and Henrys'' (Arts pages, Aug. 10):</p>
        <p>One does not need to look abroad to see Shakespearean history in the making.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Marathon of Richards and Henrys'' (Arts pages, Aug. 10):</p>
        <p>One does not need to look abroad to see Shakespearean history in the making.</p>
        <p>The Oregon Shakespeare Festival -- the country's largest regional repertory theater -- completes its  sequence of Henrys with a triumphant production of ''Henry V'' this summer.</p>
        <p>And like William Houston of the Royal Shakespeare Company, the Oregon Shakespeare Festival's Dan Donohue has followed Hal on his journey from rebellious prince to mature monarch, portraying Hal in ''Henry IV'' parts one and two before donning the crown as King Harry.</p>
        <p>DANIEL POLLACK-PELZNER  Portland, Ore., Aug. 10, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a graduate of the Oregon Shakespeare Festival's summer seminar.</p>
      </block>
